{"title_page": "Sarah Lucille Turner", "text_new": "'''Sarah Lucille Turner''', later known as '''Sarah Turner Jepson''' (March 28, 1898 \u2013 April 12, 1972), was a Missouri lawyer and politician who later went on to a career at ''[[Newsweek]]''.  With [[Mellcene Thurman Smith]], she was one of the first two women elected to the [[Missouri General Assembly]], although Smith joked that she was first woman representative because representatives were sworn in by alphabetical order.<ref name=\"Show Me MO\">{{cite book|last1=Dains|first1=Missouri Women's History Project ; sponsored by Missouri Division, American Association of University Women ; general editor, Mary K.|title=Show me Missouri women : selected biographies|date=1989|publisher=Thomas Jefferson University Press|location=Kirksville, Mo., USA|isbn=0943549051|pages=194\u2013196}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nTurner was a native of [[Centralia, Illinois]] who moved with her family to [[Kansas City, Missouri]] when she was ten.<ref name=\"nwhm.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nwhm.org/education-resources/biography/biographies/sarah-lucille-turner/|title=Education & Resources \u2013 National Women's History Museum \u2013 NWHM|work=nwhm.org|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref>  A 1915 honors graduate of [[Northeast High School (Missouri)|Northeast High School]], she took a job during the day for Havens Structural Steel Company and took night classes at the [[Kansas City School of Law]]<ref name=\"womenscouncil.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.womenscouncil.org/cd_web/Turner.html|title=Sarah Lucille Turner|work=womenscouncil.org|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref> she graduated in 1922 and began work with the law firm of Hagerman & Jost.<ref name=\"nwhm.org\"/>  She and Smith were both elected a few months after law school graduation, in 1922, and both were [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]].<ref name=\"nwhm.org1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nwhm.org/online-exhibits/legislators/Missouri.html|title=Women Wielding Power-Missouri|work=nwhm.org|accessdate=12 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906090514/https://www.nwhm.org/online-exhibits/legislators/Missouri.html|archivedate=6 September 2015}}</ref>  Otherwise, they were quite different; Turner was unmarried, unlike Smith, and was the youngest member of the House at the time of her service.<ref name=\"nwhm.org\"/>\n\nTurner had not planned to seek office, but changed her mind when some of the men in her law school classes voiced objections to the idea of\nwomen serving as office-holders.<ref name=\"womenscouncil.org\"/> Her parents objected to her decision to run.<ref name=\"ChristensenFoley1999\">{{cite book|author1=Lawrence O. Christensen|author2=William E. Foley|author3=Gary Kremer|title=Dictionary of Missouri Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6gyxWHRLAWgC|date=October 1999|publisher=University of Missouri Press|isbn=978-0-8262-6016-1}}</ref> She was the first woman to preside over the Missouri House of Representatives, on March 16, 1923. Committees on which she served included Civil and Criminal Procedure, Constitution Amendments and Criminal Jurisprudence, and University and School of Mines<ref name=\"womenscouncil.org\"/> and she chaired the Children's Code Committee.<ref name=\"nwhm.org\"/> She favored better schools and the increase of teachers' pay.<ref name=\"ChristensenFoley1999\"/> She expressed interest in legislation affecting women and children. Five of her bills were passed, and she introduced others, pertaining to children's employment, increasing appropriations for the state women's reformatory, and licensing children's boarding homes. She also introduced the legislation declaring the [[Crataegus|hawthorn]] as the [[List of U.S. state flowers|state flower]].<ref name=\"womenscouncil.org\"/> Smith and Turner both lost their bids for re-election in 1924.<ref name=\"nwhm.org1\"/> During her term Turner represented the 6th District, consisting of part of [[Jackson County, Missouri|Jackson County]], in the Legislature.<ref name=\"womenscouncil.org\"/> Besides her political career, Turner was active in [[historic preservation]] as well; she is said to have been part of the effort to save the [[George Caleb Bingham House]] and Huston Tavern in [[Arrow Rock, Missouri|Arrow Rock]],<ref name=\"kchistory.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kchistory.org/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/Local&CISOPTR=31278&CISOBOX=1&REC=8|title=Missouri Valley Special Collections : Item Viewer|work=kchistory.org|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref> both today part of [[Arrow Rock State Historic Site]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mostateparks.com/park/arrow-rock-state-historic-site|title=Arrow Rock State Historic Site|work=mostateparks.com|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter her defeat Turner moved, first to [[New York City]], where she practiced law,<ref name=\"newspapers.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/71771546/|title=The Sedalia Democrat from Sedalia, Missouri \u00b7 Page 8|work=Newspapers.com|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref> served as secretary to attorney [[Frank P. Walsh]], and worked as secretary for [[Malcolm Muir]], vice-president of [[McGraw-Hill]]. Later she moved to [[Washington, D.C.]] to work for [[Hugh S. Johnson]], who directed the [[National Recovery Act]].<ref name=\"ChristensenFoley1999\"/> In 1932 she married a real estate agent, Walter C. Jepson, a veteran of the [[United States Air Force]] who had served in both World Wars.<ref name=\"nwhm.org\"/><ref name=\"ChristensenFoley1999\"/> When Muir became the publisher of ''Newsweek'' she returned to her position as his secretary;<ref name=\"ChristensenFoley1999\"/> eventually she became the magazine's personnel manager, from which position she retired at 65.<ref name=\"nwhm.org1\"/> She and her husband then moved to  [[Southern Pines, North Carolina]], where she died of cancer.<ref name=\"nwhm.org1\"/><ref name=\"newspapers.com\"/>\n\nA small collection of material related to Turner's life and career is held by the Missouri Valley Special Collections unit of the [[Kansas City Public Library]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kchistory.org/cdm4/results.php?CISOOP1=exact&CISOFIELD1=CISOSEARCHALL&CISOROOT=all&CISOBOX1=Turner%2C+Sarah+L.|title=Missouri Valley Special Collections : Search Results|work=kchistory.org|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mary Gant]], first woman elected to the [[Missouri State Senate]], in 1979\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, Sarah Lucille}}\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Missouri House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Missouri Democrats]]\n[[Category:University of Missouri\u2013Kansas City alumni]]\n[[Category:Newsweek people]]\n[[Category:People from Centralia, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Missouri lawyers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:National Recovery Administration]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Southern Pines, North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sarah Lucille Turner''', later known as '''Sarah Turner Jepson''' (March 28, 1898 \u2013 April 12, 1972) was a Missouri lawyer and politician who later went on to a career at ''[[Newsweek]]''.  With [[Mellcene Thurman Smith]], she was one of the first two women elected to the [[Missouri General Assembly]], although Smith joked that she was first woman representative because representatives were sworn in by alphabetical order.<ref name=\"Show Me MO\">{{cite book|last1=Dains|first1=Missouri Women's History Project ; sponsored by Missouri Division, American Association of University Women ; general editor, Mary K.|title=Show me Missouri wom